      ],
      "explanation": "Active funds charge 0.5-1.5% expense ratios vs. 0.03-0.20% for index funds. The difference covers fund managers, research analysts, and trading costs. Over 30 years, a 1% higher fee on a $100,000 portfolio costs ~$100,000 in lost returns due to compounding. The SPIVA scorecard shows ~90% of active funds underperform their benchmark over 20 years, making low-cost index funds the better choice for most investors."
